## Notes and Endnotes: Chapters 5–11 (Scholarly Apparatus)

These pages are the endnotes section covering Chapters 5–11.
They contain methodological details, data source clarifications,
and supplementary arguments not fully developed in the main text.

---

### Chapter 5 Notes: Capital-Income Ratios

- **France net foreign asset position**: financial assets held by
  rest of world = 310% of national income (2010); French assets
  abroad = 300%; net position = −10%
- **US net foreign position**: −20% corresponds to ~120% of NI
  held by foreigners vs. 100% owned by US residents abroad
- **Spain vs. Japan bubble comparison**: Spain has net negative
  foreign asset position (~1 year NI) — "seriously complicates"
  Spain's situation; Japan has net positive of similar magnitude
- **US trade deficit anomaly**: deficit should produce far more
  negative net position than observed; gap explained by very high
  returns on US foreign assets (stocks) vs. low returns paid on
  US liabilities (Treasury bonds) — work of **Pierre-Olivier
  Gourinchas** and **Hélène Rey** cited
- Tax haven transfers inflate US trade deficit figures —
  fictitious transfers to US firms abroad, repatriated as profits,
  restore the balance of payments; distorts basic measurement
- **Ancient Rome land values**: R. Goldsmith (*Pre-modern
  Financial Systems*, 1987) estimates land reached 6× national
  income — even higher than modern levels
- Intergenerational wealth mobility in primitive societies varies
  widely by economic activity type (hunting, herding, farming);
  see Borgerhoff Mulder et al., *Science* 326 (2009)

---

### Chapter 6 Notes: Capital-Labor Split in the 21st Century

- **Public debt interest**: excluded from national income (pure
  transfer); if included, capital's income share would be 1–2pp
  higher (up to 4–5pp during high public debt periods)
- **Self-employed income attribution**: two methods — assign
  average labor income OR assign average capital return to
  business capital; both used in different contexts
- **Individually owned businesses**: share of domestic output
  fell from 30–40% (1950s) to ~10% (1980s) as agriculture
  declined; stabilized, rising to 12–15% with fiscal incentives
- Data for Britain from **Robert Allen**; France data from
  Piketty's own work
- **18th–19th century interest rates on public debt**:
  typically 4–5%; as low as 3% in economic slowdowns;
  rose to 5–6%+ during political tension (pre-Revolution France)
- **French "livret A" savings account** paid nominal 2% in 2013
  = real return close to zero
- **Cobb-Douglas production function**: Y = F(K,L) = K^α × L^(1−α);
  infinite elasticity = linear function Y = rK + vL where r and v
  are fixed regardless of quantities
- **Arthur Bowley** calculated capital's share ~37%, labor ~63%
  for Britain 1880–1913 — consistent with Piketty's findings
- **Jürgen Kuczynski**, *Labour Conditions in Western Europe
  1820–1935* — valuable historical source despite lacunae
- **J.M. Keynes** (1939): even he was uncertain about the
  "stable" level of the capital-labor split; insisted "manual
  labor" income seemed stable at 40% of NI (1920–1930)
- **"Robotized" economy** is the only case where return on
  capital does not tend toward zero: infinite elasticity of
  substitution between capital and labor, production ultimately
  uses capital alone
- Marx's factory accounts (*Wages, Price, and Profit*, 1865):
  profits attained 50% of value added — consistent with an
  industrial-era capital share hypothesis

---

### Chapter 7 Notes: Inequality — Preliminary Bearings

- **Balzac's currency**: used francs/livres tournois/écus
  interchangeably; since inflation was nonexistent, all stable
  and interchangeable. An écu = 5 francs; a louis d'or = 20 francs
- **Deciles defined**: adult population, individual level where
  possible; for France and US, historical data only at household
  level (incomes of both partners added)
- **Median vs. mean**: median always lower than mean because
  distributions have long upper tails; for labor income, median
  ≈ 80% of mean (e.g., average wage 2,000€/month → median ~1,600€)
- For wealth, median can be extremely low — often less than 50%
  of mean wealth, or even zero if bottom half owns almost nothing
- **Sieyès quote**: "What is the Third Estate? Everything.
  What has it been in the political order until now? Nothing.
  What does it want? To become something."
- Pensions and unemployment insurance included in primary labor
  income (as "deferred wages") — otherwise inequality of adult
  income would be noticeably and artificially higher
- **"Ideal society"** (Table 7.2): even there, richest 10% own
  more capital than poorest 50%; richest 1% has average wealth
  20× greater than poorest 50% (group 5× larger)
- **Top decile's share of financial/business capital**: 70–80%
  or more — firm ownership remains abstract for vast majority
- **François Quesnay's *Tableau économique*** (1758): first
  synthetic picture of economy and exchanges between social groups;
  early precursor to "social tables" methodology
- **Branko Milanovic**, *The Haves and the Have-Nots* (2010):
  cited for historical global inequality measurement

---

### Chapter 8 Notes: Two Worlds (France & US Income Inequality)

- French income tax instituted **1914**; *cédulaire* wage tax
  adopted 1917 → separate annual measures of high income and
  high wages from those dates
- Method initially introduced by **Simon Kuznets** — use fiscal
  data plus national accounts
- **Fractile notation**: P90–95 = richest 10%, lower half;
  P95–99 = next 4%; P99–99.5 = poorer half of top 1%;
  P99.5–99.9 = next 0.4%; P99.9–99.99 = top 0.09%;
  P99.99–100 = top 0.01% (ten-thousandth)
- **Top centile in France 2010**: 500,000 adults out of 50 million
- **Wages in P99–99.5 and P99.5–99.9**: 50–60% of income
  (vs. 20–30% for mixed incomes) — high salaried incomes
  dominate high mixed incomes almost as much as interwar years
- **Capital income understatement**: since 1960 fiscal data
  exclude "fictive rents" (imputed rental value of owner-occupied
  housing); if included, capital's share among "the 9 percent"
  would reach or exceed 20% in 2000–2010
- **WWII French tax administration**: continued collecting and
  compiling income statistics throughout war "as if nothing had
  changed" — mechanical data processing (punched cards) made
  rapid cross-tabulations possible; statistical publications
  "richer than ever before"
- **Top decile's share** fell from 47% to 29% of NI during
  WWII; top centile from 21% to 7%
- **Wage compression began before WWII**: wage hierarchy
  compression started in **1936** with the **Matignon Accords**
- **Reagan tax reform (1986)**: suspicious jump in top incomes
  around this time — firms changed legal form to have profits
  taxed as personal rather than corporate income (purely
  short-term fiscal effect, not structural)
- **Paul Krugman**, *The Conscience of a Liberal* (2007) and
  **Joseph Stiglitz**, *The Price of Inequality* (2012):
  both illustrate attachment to the mid-20th century egalitarian
  period as a reference point
- Top income share understatement: correction for capital income
  might add 2–3pp to upper decile's share (uncorrected: 49.7%
  in 2007, 47.9% in 2010)
- Inequality rise **not compensated by greater intergenerational
  mobility** — quite the contrary (see Chapter 13)

---

### Chapter 9 Notes: Inequality of Labor Income

- **Goldin & Katz**, *The Race between Education and Technology*
  (2010): key reference for US educational wage differentials
- Health and education expenditures counted as **consumption**
  in national accounts (not investment) — another reason
  "human capital" framing is problematic
- **US minimum wage history**: 1935 legislation struck down by
  Supreme Court; **Roosevelt** reintroduced it 1938 and
  ultimately prevailed; increased ~10% in 1998–2002 to offset
  workweek reduction (39→35 hours, same monthly wage)
- **Card & Krueger**, *Myth and Measurement* (1995): "monopsony"
  case — single employer as price-setter for labor; minimum wage
  increase doesn't reduce employment when profit margins are
  large; employment may even increase (more people seek work)
- **Rebecca Blank**, *Changing Inequality* (2011): almost
  entirely focused on college diploma wage gap — misses top 1%
  explosion because survey data (not tax records) are used
- **Raghuram Rajan**, *Fault Lines* (2010): also overestimates
  education/inequality link relative to top 1% explosion
- **Capital gains and US top share**: if included, top centile's
  share exceeds 20% of NI in the 2000s
- **Pareto coefficient**: in egalitarian countries (Sweden 1970s),
  top 0.1% earns barely 2× the top 1%; in highly inegalitarian
  (US 2000s), top thousandth earns 4–5× the top centile
- **"0.1 percent" income levels**:
  - France/Japan: rose from 15× to 25× national average
    (450,000 → 750,000€/year at 30,000€ average)
  - United States: rose from 20× to 100× national average
    ($600,000 → $3 million/year)
- **Superentrepreneurs** (Bill Gates type): so few as to be
  irrelevant for income analysis; relevant only for analysis
  of fortunes and evolution of different wealth classes
- **Stock options accounting**: if manager buys $100 stock for
  $50 via option when it's worth $200, the $100 difference is
  treated as wage income in year exercised; subsequent gain
  ($250−$200=$50) recorded as capital gain
- **CEO pay research**: Bertrand & Mullainathan, "Are CEOs
  Rewarded for Luck?" *QJE* (2001); Bebchuk & Fried,
  *Pay without Performance* (2004)
- **India "black hole"**: per capita income grew ~4%/year
  (national accounts) vs. ~2%/year (household surveys)
  1990–2000 — the gap = nearly half of total growth
  (Banerjee & Piketty, *World Bank Economic Review*, 2005)

---

### Chapter 10 Notes: Inequality of Capital Ownership

- **"Mortality multiplier" method**: reweights each observation
  by inverse of mortality rate in age cohort — person dying at 40
  represents more living individuals than one dying at 80;
  developed by **B. Mallet, M.J. Séaillès, H.C. Strutt,
  J.C. Stamp** (1900–1910); validated against Nordic wealth tax
  data and French wealth tax (1990–2010)
- **Paris archives data** (with **Gilles Postel-Vinay** and
  **Jean-Laurent Rosenthal**): individual estate statements
  from Parisian and French national archives
- Wealth concentration data: top centile >60% of all inheritable
  wealth; bottom half owns nothing
- **US top centile ownership ~1800**: some estimates put it
  below 15% of total national wealth — but these focus only on
  free individuals (controversial); Piketty uses entire
  population (free and unfree)
- **Willford I. King**, *Wealth and Income of the People of the
  United States* (MacMillan, 1915): compared US states with
  European (Prussian tax) estimates; found differences much
  smaller than initially expected
- **Pareto "inverted coefficients"**: range 1.5–3.5;
  - 1.5 = low inequality (individuals above threshold own on
    average 1.5× threshold level)
  - 3.5 = very high inequality; top 0.1% earns 5× the top 1%
- **Ancient Rome land rent**: annual returns ~5%; interest on
  loans typically 6–8% even with real estate collateral
  (Homer & Sylla, *A History of Interest Rates*, 1996)
- **Swedish wealth dynamics (1900–1910)**: lower capital/income
  ratio than France/Britain (lower land values, foreign-owned
  domestic capital); primogeniture until end of 19th century;
  net result: wealth less concentrated than Britain,
  close to French level
- **National solidarity tax (France, August 15, 1945)**:
  exceptional levy on all wealth as of June 4, 1945; rates up
  to 20% for largest fortunes; plus exceptional levy on all
  nominal wealth increases 1940–1945 at up to 100%;
  in practice (given tripling of prices), effectively a 100%
  tax on anyone who didn't "sufficiently suffer" during the war
- **r > g mechanism**: sufficient by itself to explain observed
  concentration levels, but does not claim to be the only force;
  various contradictory forces may balance each other
- **Infinite horizon model**: implies infinite elasticity of
  saving → assumes tax policy cannot affect supply of capital;
  equilibrium r = θ + γ×g (θ = time preference, γ = concavity
  of utility function; typically γ ∈ [1.5, 2.5])

---

### Chapter 11 Notes: Merit and Inheritance in the Long Run

- **Inheritance data methodology**: Piketty, "On the Long-Run
  Evolution of Inheritance: France 1820–2050," *QJE* 126,
  no. 3 (2011): 1071–131
- **Cohort size in France**: ~800,000–850,000 births/year
  from late 1940s to early 2010s (stable); 19th century had
  ~1 million births but high infant mortality
- **"Rate of estate devolution"** theory popular in France
  1880–1910: **Albert de Foville, Clément Colson, Pierre Emile
  Levasseur** showed national wealth ≈ 30× annual inheritance
  flow ("estate multiplier" also used in England by Giffen)
- **Becker's meritocracy claim**: never explicit, but implicit
  in his work that rising human capital eclipses inherited wealth;
  ignores that top decile always owns >60% of inheritable wealth
  while bottom half owns nothing
- **Inheritance flow → wage income ratio**: ~3× larger in 18th
  and 19th centuries and 21st century (inheritance ≈ ¼ of
  resources); ~10× larger in the 20th century (inheritance ≈ 1/10)
- **19th century Paris real estate**: beyond reach of modestly
  wealthy; **César Birotteau** (Balzac character) rejected wife's
  advice to invest in good farms near Chinon as "too staid"
  — "bold and forward-looking — unfortunately for him"
- **Napoleon's *majorat* (1807)**: allowed certain landed estates
  linked to titles of nobility to pass to eldest males;
  **Charles X** tried to restore *substitutions héréditaires*
  in 1826 for his own nobility; both definitively abolished 1848
- **Women and Civil Code**: formally equal rights in dividing
  estates, but wife could not freely manage bank accounts or
  sell property — asymmetry persisted until 1970s
- **Arthur Young** (October 1788, *Travels in France*): "Europe
  is now so much assimilated that if one goes to a house where
  the fortune is 15 or 20,000 livres a year, we shall find in
  the mode of living much more resemblance than a young traveller
  will ever be prepared to look for" — 15,000–20,000 livres =
  30–50× average income; could afford 6 men-servants, 5 maids,
  8 horses, garden, and regular table
- **Vautrin's lecture** verification: only ~5 lawyers in Paris
  earned >50,000 francs/year (100× average income) —
  consistent with Balzac's portrayal
- **Napoleon's civil service pay scale**: small number of
  highly paid posts (generals, ambassadors, prefects, magistrates)
  costing ~3 million francs; **Thiers (1831)** saw little reason
  to reduce them; **Tocqueville** noted that highest US civil
  servants were paid much less than French counterparts —
  a "sure sign democratic spirit prevailed"
- **Revolutionary pay scale attempt (1792)**: tried to limit
  ratio to 8:1; finally adopted in 1948 but quickly circumvented
  by opaque bonuses for highest civil servants (persists today)
- **Thorstein Veblen**, *The Theory of the Leisure Class* (1899):
  egalitarian US dream was already "a distant memory" by then
- **Tax asymmetry**: labor income taxed ~30% on average;
  average effective tax rate on inheritances <5% — even though
  inheritance gives rise to same rights as labor income regarding
  transfers in kind (education, health, security) financed by taxes
- **Durkheim's theory** (*De la division du travail social*, 1893):
  predicted end of inheritance as a political theory;
  prediction no more accurate than others; wars of 20th century
  may have merely postponed the problem to the 21st century
- **British suffrage history**: <2% of British population could
  vote until 1831; reforms of 1867, 1884, and 1918 gradually
  ended property qualifications; in France under Restoration,
  <1% of adult males had right to vote (90,000 of 10 million)

<!-- pp. 661-680 -->

## Notes: Chapters 12–16 (Endnotes Section)

These pages are the endnotes for Chapters 12–16, containing
substantive methodological clarifications, data sources,
historical episodes, and analytical extensions not in the
main text.

---

### Chapter 12: Global Inequality of Wealth — Notes

- **Global GDP** (2012–2013): ~$85 trillion (PPP); total private
  wealth ~$340 trillion (~4× GDP)
- **Inflation** averaged 2–2.5%/year in this period (lower in
  euros than dollars)
- **Top twenty-millionth fractile** (1,400 billionaires): if
  divergence rate observed 1987–2013 continues, their share
  rises from 1.5% of global wealth (2013) → 7.2% (2050) →
  59.6% (2100) — a staggering extrapolation
- **Forbes methodology flaw**: excludes "despots" and those
  whose fortune depends on "political position," but admits
  oligarchs who acquired wealth before taking power
  (e.g., Georgian oligarch **Bidzina Ivanishvili**, $5B fortune
  = 1/4 of Georgia's GDP, still listed in 2013)
- **Top ten-thousandth** (450 adults of 45B): avg fortune ~50M
  euros, ~1,000× global average; their share = ~10% of total
  global wealth
- **Bill Gates**: Forbes #1 from 1995 to 2007; displaced by
  **Warren Buffett** (2008–09), then **Carlos Slim** (2010–13)
- **L'Oréal origin**: dyes invented 1907 named "L'Auréale";
  French Company for Harmless Hair Dyes (1909) → L'Oréal
  (1936). Parallel to Balzac's fictional César Birotteau
  (who made fortune from "L'Eau Carminative")
- **Billionaire consumption is negligible**: with 10B euros
  capital at 5% return, only 0.1% needed for 10M/year
  consumption; at 10%, 99% can be reinvested — wealth grows
  regardless of lifestyle
- **University endowments**: total US university capital =
  ~3% of GDP; annual income = ~0.2% of GDP (>10% of total
  higher education expenditure). For most-endowed schools,
  endowment income = 30–40% of resources
- **Harvard endowment detail**: averaged ~10% real return
  1990–2010; new gifts added ~2%/year; total real income =
  12% of endowment. Of that, 5% used for expenses, 7%
  reinvested → grew from $5B (1990) to nearly $30B (2010),
  while spending 2.5× what it received in gifts
- **Sovereign wealth funds**: own ~5% of global net financial
  assets; oil rent exceeded 5% of global GDP from
  mid-1970s to mid-1980s
- **Forbes and foundations**: Gates Foundation assets counted
  as Gates's fortune because he retains effective control —
  incompatible with "disinterested gift"
- **Bernard Arnault** (LVMH): Belgian foundation "neither
  charitable nor fiscal" — explicitly an estate vehicle.
  Quote: "Among my five children and two nephews, there is
  surely one who will prove capable of taking over after I
  am gone." Forces heirs to vote "indissociably" to ensure
  group survival

> "The divergence of the petroleum exporters can be seen as an
> oligarchic divergence, moreover, because petroleum rents go
> to a small number of individuals, who may be able to sustain
> a high level of accumulation through sovereign wealth funds."
> — Note 49

- **Tax haven hidden wealth** (Gabriel Zucman, *QJE* 2013):
  Europe and US are net debtors only because offshore assets
  are unrecorded; if counted, Europe's net position turns
  strongly positive
- **Roine & Waldenström** on Sweden: accounting for assets
  held abroad puts Swedish top centile close to the US top
  centile level (which itself should also be adjusted upward)

---

### Chapter 13: A Social State for the Twenty-First Century — Notes

- **Tax definition**: includes all taxes, fees, social
  contributions, compulsory payments; "taxes" used
  colloquially but always includes these throughout the book
- **Military spending**: minimum 2–3% of national income;
  US currently >4%; Saudi Arabia and Gulf states >10%
- **19th-century baseline**: health and education budgets
  below 1–2% of national income (reference: **P. Lindert**,
  *Growing Public*, Cambridge, 2004)
- **Tax as % of national income vs. GDP**: national income
  ≈ 90% of GDP (after ~10% capital depreciation). Shares
  expressed as % of NI are ~10% larger than % of GDP
  (e.g., 50% of NI = 45% of GDP)
- **UK Thatcherite phase**: taxes fell several points in 1980s,
  then climbed again 1990–2000 as new governments reinvested
  in public services
- **Social spending breakdown**: typically 5–6% NI for
  education, 8–9% for health
- **NHS significance**: established 1948; so central to
  British identity it was dramatized in the 2012 Olympic
  opening ceremonies alongside the Industrial Revolution
- **US health inefficiency**: adding private insurance, US
  spends nearly 20% of NI on healthcare vs. 10–12% in
  Europe — more expensive, with worse coverage and health
  outcomes
- **Beveridgian vs. Bismarckian pensions**: flat pension for
  all (Britain) vs. proportional to wages (France, where
  ceiling is 8× average wage vs. 2–3× in most countries)
- **US carceral state substitutes for welfare state** for
  childless individuals: ~1% of adult US population
  imprisoned (2013), highest in world. For adult black
  males, rate >5%. Food stamps requirement seen as
  inconsistent with liberal values — reflects racial
  prejudice reinforcing economic prejudice
- **Rawls quote**: "Social and economic inequalities … are
  just only if they result in compensating benefits for
  everyone, and in particular for the least advantaged
  members of society" (*A Theory of Justice*, 1971;
  repeated in *Political Liberalism*, 1993)
- **Intergenerational mobility**: correlation coefficients of
  earned income range 0.2–0.3 (Sweden/Finland) to 0.5–0.6
  (US); Britain 0.4–0.5; Germany/France ~0.4
- **Harvard undergraduate cost** (2012–13): $54,000/year
  including room and board; tuition alone $38,000. Some
  universities more expensive despite higher endowments
- **British university tuition trajectory**: £1,000 (1998) →
  £3,000 (2004) → £9,000 (2012). Share of tuition in total
  university resources now close to 1920s levels and US levels
- **Sciences Po (Paris) tuition**: ranges from zero (lowest
  income) to 10,000 euros/year (income >200,000 euros) —
  effectively a privatized progressive income tax that
  benefits own children, not others
- **Income-contingent loans** (Australia/Britain): not repaid
  until graduate reaches income threshold; effectively an
  additional income tax on students of modest background
  while wealthy students receive untaxed gifts from parents
- **PAYGO volatility rationale**: introduced post-WWII because
  people who saved via financial markets in 1920–30 were
  ruined; no political will to repeat capitalized pension
  experiment. Sweden's 1990s reform modernized this
- **Trade liberalization fiscal cost**: Julia Cagé and Lucie
  Gadenne show developing countries lose significant fiscal
  revenues from trade liberalization — complicates social
  state development in poor countries
- **China vs. India income inequality**: Piketty and Nancy
  Qian (*AEJ: Applied Economics*, 2009) — difference closely
  related to greater prevalence of **wage labor in China**;
  fiscal/social state construction and wage-earner status
  go together historically

---

### Chapter 14: Rethinking the Progressive Income Tax — Notes

- **Nicholas Kaldor's progressive consumption tax**: proposed
  as complement to (not substitute for) income and estate
  taxes, to prevent circumvention
- **France's poll tax analogy**: poll tax adopted 1988,
  abolished 1991 — same payment from every adult regardless
  of income/wealth; regressive by construction
- **French income tax complexity**: only developed country
  not withholding income tax at source; many special
  categories and overlapping taxes; exceptionally opaque
  and regressive in practice
- **French estate/gift tax**: average rate barely 5% even
  for top centile of inheritances — far below statutory rates
- **1914 French income tax**: *impôt général sur le revenu*
  (IGR) — progressive tax on total income, forerunner of
  today's system. Modified 1917 into *cédulaire* system
  taxing income categories differently (forerunner of
  corporate tax). Reference: Piketty, *Les hauts revenus en
  France*, 233–334
- **Progressive income tax originally targeted capital
  income**: everyone knew capital dominated the income
  hierarchy; exemptions for capital income would have seemed
  absurd to early 20th-century reformers
- **Joseph Caillaux** (French finance minister) upon seeing
  estate tax data: "I have been led to believe and to say
  that France was a country of small fortunes…. The
  statistics … force us to retreat from this position…. a
  small number of people possess the bulk of this country's
  wealth." (*L'impôt sur le revenu*, 1910)
- **US "family compensation tax"** (1920–1951): surcharge
  of 25% for unmarried taxpayers without children; under
  certain conditions top rate would have been 62% (1920)
  or 90% (1925). Renamed "family compensation tax" 1939–44
- **Record tax rates**: Britain's 98% top rate in force
  1941–52 and again 1974–78; capital income also taxed
  at 98% (labor income 83%)
- **George McGovern** (1972 US presidential campaign):
  proposed 100% top inheritance tax rate as part of
  guaranteed minimum income plan. His crushing defeat by
  Nixon "marked the beginning of the end of the United
  States' enthusiasm for redistribution"
- **Josiah Wedgwood**, *The Economics of Inheritance* (1929):
  showed charitable giving was "of little consequence"; only
  taxation could achieve equalization desired; showed French
  estates were nearly as concentrated as British (1910),
  concluding equal division of estates alone was not enough
- **No evidence** that executives 1950–1980 were compensated
  in kind (private planes, offices) to make up for high top
  rates — all evidence suggests such benefits have
  *increased* since 1980 (undermining the argument that
  high taxes led to hidden compensation)
- **Optimal top income tax rate**: Piketty, Saez, Stantcheva
  (*AEJ: Economic Policy*, forthcoming) — no statistically
  significant relationship between decreasing top marginal
  rate and GDP growth rate across 18 OECD countries.
  Elasticity of labor supply can be ruled out at >0.1–0.2,
  justifying high optimal marginal rates (~82%)
- **Xavier Gabaix and Augustin Landier** argued skyrocketing
  CEO pay is mechanical consequence of increased firm size;
  Piketty's rebuttal: company size increased similarly
  everywhere but pay only spiked in Anglo-Saxon countries —
  theory cannot explain international variation
- **Progressive tax serves two distinct functions**:
  (1) confiscatory rates (80–90%) on top 0.5–1% to end
  "indecent and useless compensation"; (2) high but
  non-confiscatory rates (50–60%) on top 5–10% to raise
  revenue for social state

---

### Chapter 15: A Global Tax on Capital — Notes

- **Custodian banks/clearing houses**: private institutions
  track ownership of securities but for the issuing company,
  not for individual wealth records; no comprehensive
  registry of individual asset ownership exists
- **Fall of Rome and cadastre**: fall of Roman Empire ended
  the imperial land tax and cadastre; **Peter Temin** argues
  this contributed to economic chaos in early Middle Ages
  (*The Roman Market Economy*, Princeton, 2012)
- **"Hedonic" regression** used by authorities to calculate
  market price of real estate as function of property
  characteristics — transactional data available in all
  developed countries
- **Self-reporting bias in wealth taxes**: France's ISF
  produces abnormally large number of declarations just
  below taxable threshold; tendency to understate real
  estate value by 10–20%
- **French wealth tax (ISF)**: applies above 1.3M euros (with
  30% deduction on primary residence); rates 0.7–1.5% on
  highest bracket (>10M euros). But generates <0.5% of GDP
  — wealthiest largely avoid it through "business asset"
  exemptions and "stockholder agreements"
- **French government's archaic wealth disclosure method**
  (2013): turned to asking ministers to self-declare assets
  after one minister was caught lying about Swiss account
- **Tax haven losses**: Luxembourg/Switzerland may lose
  10–20% of national income to tax haven activity; exotic
  microstates functioning solely as fictitious corporate
  domiciles may lose 50–80%
- **Bettencourt fortune income example**: at even 2% return
  on 30B euros → 600M euros/year economic income, not the
  5M euros declared (difference is unrealized capital gains
  not captured by income tax)
- **Bettencourt political scandal**: family trust managed by
  wife of budget minister, whose party received large
  donations from Bettencourt and had reduced the wealth tax
  by two-thirds while in power — minister later resigned
  after secret Swiss account revealed
- **Maurice Allais** (*L'impôt sur le capital*, 1977):
  advocated eliminating all other taxes in favor of sole
  capital tax — Piketty calls this "extravagant and not very
  sensible." Capital tax is useful but cannot replace all
  other taxes
- **Optimal capital tax formula**: t = 1 − G/R, where G =
  generational growth rate, R = generational return on
  capital. Approaches 100% when growth → 0; approaches 0%
  when growth → return on capital
- **Thomas Paine**, *Agrarian Justice* (1795): proposed 10%
  inheritance tax on "unaccumulated" estates; direct-line
  transmission debates in French Revolution set rate at
  only 2%
- **Swedish capital tax history**: created 1947, suspended
  1997 (law never formally repealed). Rates generally under
  2%; peak 4% (1983, assessed values unrelated to market).
  Abolished 2005, partly due to fiscal competition pressure
  — "a good example of the growing inability of smaller
  countries to maintain an independent fiscal policy"
- **German capital tax**: created in Prussia, suspended 1997,
  abolished 2007; referenced in **Fabien Dell**, *L'Allemagne
  inégale*, PhD diss., Paris School of Economics, 2008
- **European proposed capital tax revenue**: ~2.5% of European
  adults own >1M euros; 0.2% own >5M euros. Annual revenue
  at proposed rates (~300B euros on 15T GDP). Top centile
  owns ~25% of total wealth = ~125% of European GDP

---

### Chapter 16: The Question of the Public Debt — Notes

- **Europe's net asset position**: if assets hidden in tax
  havens counted, Europe turns from net debtor to
  significantly net creditor vs. rest of world
- **Germany's WWII debt cancellation**: Allies cancelled much
  of Germany's debt after WWII (repayment postponed to
  reunification, which never occurred). German historian
  **Albrecht Ritschl** calculates these amounts would be
  substantial if recapitalized — includes occupation fees
  levied on Greece. Complicates Germany's current insistence
  on pure austerity logic for others
- **Debt-to-GDP math**: if GDP grows 2%/year and debt grows
  1%/year, debt-to-GDP ratio falls ~1%/year
- **One-time capital tax vs. primary surplus**: analytically
  equivalent ways to reduce debt, but capital tax concentrates
  burden on the very wealthy, while austerity spreads it
  across entire population (and generally spares the wealthy)
- **1920s savings wiped out**: stock market crash destroyed
  interwar savings; inflation 1945–48 delivered additional
  shock → "old-age minimum" created 1956, PAYGO pension
  system created 1945
- **European Redemption Pact**: German Council of Economic
  Experts *Annual Report 2011* proposed redemption fund;
  Piketty notes "redemption" language (connoting long
  suffering by entire population) may sit poorly with
  progressive capital tax as alternative framework
- **Immigration rates** (2000–2010): permanent immigration
  reached 0.6–0.7%/year of receiving country population
  in Italy, Spain, Sweden, Britain; 0.4% in US; 0.2–0.3%
  in France and Germany — European levels roughly comparable
  to North American during this period
- **China's People's Assembly wealth**: average net worth
  of 70 richest members >$1B (Hurun Report 2012); US House
  of Representatives members average only $15M. Piketty
  notes Assembly membership is largely honorific for
  billionaires — better compared to top 70 US political
  donors than to legislators

<!-- pp. 681-700 -->

## Back Matter: Endnotes (Chapters 15–16 and Conclusion) + Contents in Detail

*These pages contain substantive endnotes with Piketty's qualifications, historical
examples, and citations — followed by the detailed table of contents and figure list.*

---

### Endnotes — Chapter 15–16 (Selected Substantive Notes)

**On inflation and Eurozone breakup (note 16)**
- Printing money can reduce public debt via inflation, but distributive consequences
  are hard to control — whether using the euro, franc, mark, or lira
- **Nominal rigidity**: late 19th-century deflation was resented because employers
  and workers waited for *other* prices to fall before accepting their own cuts;
  key argument for 2% inflation target is it allows easier relative wage/price adjustment

**On the nature of money creation (note 20)**
- Clarifies there is no literal "money printing press": central bank loans to
  government are recorded on books — the loan must be repaid
- France 1944–48: even in chaotic conditions, money creation is a bookkeeping entry
- Central banks can *redistribute* monetary wealth but cannot *create* new wealth
- Bank of Japan balance sheet reached ~40% of GDP (summer 2013); historical peak
  was France 1944–45 at 90–100% of GDP, then reduced to nothing by inflation

**On ECB and Greek crisis (note 26)**
- Key moment: ECB's December 2009 announcement it would no longer accept Greek bonds
  as collateral if downgraded — nothing in its statutes *required* this decision

**On European "budgetary parliament" (note 28)**
- Proposed body: ~50 members per large Eurozone country, prorated by population;
  drawn from financial/social affairs committees of national parliaments
- 2012 European treaty created only a "conference of national parliaments" —
  purely consultative, no power, no common debt authority

**On Cyprus crisis and flat deposit tax (note 29)**
- Virtually flat tax on deposits reportedly requested by Cypriot president to
  protect large depositors from fleeing; illustrates the **tax competition trap**:
  small countries may engage in "ruthless tax competition to attract capital,
  even from the most disreputable sources"
- Negotiations took place entirely behind closed doors — full truth unknowable

**On France's political paralysis re: Europe (note 30–31)**
- France traumatized by 2005 referendum defeat on European Constitutional Treaty
  (whose main provisions were later adopted *without* referendum)
- Under **François Hollande**: rhetorically favored debt mutualization but made
  no concrete proposal; pretended each country could decide its own debt level —
  "impossible" since mutualization requires collective vote on total debt size
- **Bundesbank** president regularly issues statements that "a credit card cannot
  be shared without agreement on how much can be spent"

**On Google's tax argument (note 33)**
- Tech companies' logic: "We contribute far more wealth than profits/salaries suggest,
  so it's reasonable to pay low taxes" — this is a **positive externality** claim
- Problem: every actor can claim this; Google has offered no evidence it actually
  provides net positive externality; impossible to run a society where each
  individual sets their own tax rate

**On Belgian "allowance for corporate equity" (note 36)**
- Belgium 2006: allows deduction from taxable profits equal to "normal" return on equity,
  meant to equalize tax treatment of debt and equity
- Germany and France instead limit interest deductions — IMF/European Commission
  claim the approaches are equivalent, but Piketty disagrees: if you deduct normal
  return on *both* debt and equity, the **corporate tax simply disappears**

**On VAT and consumption taxes (note 37)**
- European governments favor VAT partly because it functions as a de facto tax on
  imports and competitive devaluation tool — but this is a **zero-sum game** that
  vanishes if all countries do the same; symptom of monetary union with low
  international cooperation

**On financial transaction tax (note 38)**
- Purpose is to reduce high-frequency trading (a good thing), but by definition
  the tax dries up its own revenue source; estimates of potential revenue are
  optimistic — maximum ~0.5% of GDP; cannot target individual income/wealth levels

**On the Golden Rule of accumulation (note 40)**
- References **Edmund Phelps**, "The Golden Rule of Accumulation: A Fable for
  Growthmen," *American Economic Review* 51, no. 4 (1961): 638–43
- Similar ideas (without the golden rule label) in **Maurice Allais**, *Économie
  et intérêt* (1947) and articles by **Von Neumann** (1945) and **Malinvaud** (1953)
- None of this theoretical work discusses what level of accumulation would actually
  make *r* equal to *g*

**On dynamic inefficiency and the golden rule (note 42)**
- Beyond golden-rule capital level, return on capital falls below growth rate;
  capital's long-run share < savings rate — "absurd in social terms" since maintaining
  capital stock costs more than it returns
- This "**dynamic inefficiency**" can occur if people save for old age with long
  life expectancy, ignoring return; efficient response: state issues public debt to
  reduce capital stock (replace capitalized pension with PAYGO)
- Key empirical observation: **in all known societies, average return on capital
  has always exceeded the growth rate** — dynamic inefficiency is theoretical, not observed

**On postwar social-democratic ideal (note 43)**
- Tax on capital (or public ownership) can ensure capital income < savings rate
  without excessive accumulation — "profits should finance investment, not high life
  of stockholders"
- **Helmut Schmidt** (German chancellor): *"Today's profits are tomorrow's investments
  and the day after tomorrow's jobs."* — capital and labor as partners, not adversaries
- Depends critically on institutions: taxes and public ownership; not automatic

**On Keynes and capital saturation (note 44)**
- In *The General Theory* (1936), Chapters 16 and 24, **Keynes** discusses
  "**euthanasia of the rentier**" — accumulating so much capital that returns disappear
- But Keynes is vague about *how much* capital this requires; does not mention r = g;
  does not explicitly discuss public accumulation

**On the "modified golden rule" and climate (note 45, 52)**
- **r = θ + γ × g** (modified golden rule): depends on **concavity of utility function**
- Infinite concavity → leave no capital to future (Rawlsian); go all the way to
  golden rule → leave them decades of national income as capital
- **Nicholas Stern** vs. **William Nordhaus** climate debate: both use modified
  golden rule but choose opposite ends of the concavity spectrum
- **Roger Guesnerie** and **Thomas Sterner**: natural capital is not infinitely
  substitutable — if destroyed, fewer iPhones won't compensate

**On Supreme Court blocking income tax (note 49)**
- US Supreme Court blocked federal income tax attempts in late 19th/early 20th centuries;
  blocked minimum wage legislation in 1930s; found slavery and racial discrimination
  compatible with constitutional rights for ~two centuries
- French Constitutional Court: deliberated on maximum constitutional income tax rate,
  hesitated between 65% and 67%, wondered whether to include the carbon tax

**On Italian debt burden (note 50)**
- 1970–2010: interest payments on Italian debt averaged **7% of GDP** — "astronomical"
- Primary deficit in most countries was close to zero; the *interest burden* was
  the actual problem, not overspending

**On Stern/Nordhaus discount rate (note 52)**
- Nordhaus makes a more **Rawlsian** choice than Stern regarding concavity of utility,
  which paradoxically leads him to ascribe *less* weight to future generations'
  preferences — a logically counterintuitive result

**On transparency and the 1789–90 compendium of pensions (note 57)**
- One of first acts of French Revolutionary assemblies (1789–90): compiled a
  "compendium of pensions" listing by name 23,000 individuals receiving royal payments,
  with amounts, ministry, age, and reasons — a **1,600-page book** published April 1790
- Demonstrates that financial transparency is politically achievable when there is will

**On published accounts hiding wage/profit split (note 58)**
- Wages aggregated with intermediate inputs in firm accounts; published data never
  reveal profit vs. wage split; allows **abuse of intermediate consumption** as
  mechanism to augment executive income or stockholder returns
- Example: **Lonmin accounts** and **Marikana mine** (South Africa massacre context)

**On Jacques Rancière (note 59)**
- Philosophy of **Jacques Rancière** on democracy cited as essential: his
  *La haine de la démocratie* (La Fabrique, 2005) — "the hatred of democracy"

---

### Endnotes — Conclusion

**Note 1**: An increase in growth rate *g* would also likely raise *r*,
so the gap *r − g* would not necessarily shrink — growth alone cannot solve
the inequality problem mechanically

**Note 2**: **Jean-Paul Sartre**, **Louis Althusser**, **Alain Badiou** on
their Marxist/communist commitments — Piketty observes that for these
philosophers, capital and class inequality seem of "only moderate interest"
and serve "mainly as a pretext for jousts of a different nature entirely"

