### Contents in Detail (Structure Overview)

*Pages 687–696 contain the full detailed table of contents — 16 chapters across
4 parts, plus Introduction and Conclusion. Key structural points:*

- **Part One**: Income and Capital (Chapters 1–2)
- **Part Two**: Dynamics of the Capital/Income Ratio (Chapters 3–6)
- **Part Three**: The Structure of Inequality (Chapters 7–12)
- **Part Four**: Regulating Capital in the Twenty-First Century (Chapters 13–16)

---

### Tables and Illustrations (pp. 697–700)

*Lists all data tables and figures; notable for the scope of historical data:*

- Tables span: world GDP distribution, growth since Industrial Revolution,
  demographic growth, savings rates, inequality of labor/capital income,
  Parisian portfolio composition 1872–1912, age-wealth profiles 1820–2010,
  global wealth growth 1987–2013, university endowment returns 1980–2010
- Figures include time series from **Antiquity to 2100** (projections),
  covering capital/income ratios, wealth inequality, inheritance flows,
  income inequality, minimum wages, and inheritance tax rates across
  France, Britain, Germany, US, Sweden, Europe — the empirical backbone
  of the entire book's argument

